On the Peoples Called Mankind

From the collected lectures of Archivist Solenne, Keeper Survey Office, Midgaard

They were not the first to walk the land, nor the strongest, nor the
most attuned to the currents of power that run beneath the world.
What humans were, from the earliest records we possess, was
relentless.

They built the Keeper road networks that connect the civilized lands,
stone by stone, treaty by treaty. They raised the Great Pyramid
in an age when other peoples thought such ambition was madness. They
established the Salt Ledger Kingdoms, whose trade laws still
echo in every merchant contract written today. They founded
Midgaard and Kowloon — cities that became the twin poles
of governance and commerce for the known world.

They also built the Spirebound Conclave, whose sealed experiments
left scars on the forest that have not healed. They drafted the
sealed warrants whose contents Midgaard's own courts will not
unseal. The world's greatest achievements and its worst failures both
trace back to human decisions, made within human institutions, recorded
in human ledgers.

Their defining quality is not strength or cunning. It is institutional
urgency — an almost feverish need to create systems of governance,
law, and record-keeping. Other peoples find this impulse both admirable
and alarming. A human who encounters a problem builds a bureau to
address it. A human who encounters a bureau that has failed builds
another bureau to oversee the first.

The Khenari say that humans fear death less than they fear dying
without having filed the proper documents. This is meant as mockery.
It is also, in the estimation of this archivist, not entirely wrong.

They are everywhere. They will outlast us all — not because they
are stronger, but because they will not stop building.
